  "prompt": "What is fiscal capacity distance?",
  "response": "Fiscal capacity distance is a concept used in public finance and regional economics to measure the difference in fiscal resources or ability to generate revenue between different jurisdictions or levels of government. Here are key points about fiscal capacity distance:\n\n1. Definition:\n- Measures the gap in potential revenue-raising capabilities\n- Compares the financial resources that different regions or governments can theoretically generate\n\n2. Key Components:\n- Potential tax base\n- Economic structure\n- Income levels\n- Local economic conditions\n\n3. Purpose:\n- Helps identify disparities in fiscal resources\n- Assists in designing intergovernmental transfer systems\n- Supports policy decisions related to resource allocation\n\n4. Calculation:\n- Usually involves comparing tax bases or potential revenue generation\n- Can be measured using various statistical methods\n- Often considers per capita income, economic indicators, and potential tax revenues\n\n5. Significance:\n- Important for understanding regional economic inequalities\n- Useful in designing equalization payments or fiscal transfer mechanisms\n- Helps policymakers address financial disparities between different regions\n\nThe concept is particularly relevant in federal systems and regional economic planning, where understanding fiscal capacities can inform more balanced and equitable resource distribution.",
